      <h1>The Human History of Sehome Hill</h1>
      <p>
        The human history of Sehome Hill Arboretum is layered and greater than
        what can be accounted for on a single website. The history covered here
        encompasses an overview of settler-colonialist activity on the hill and
        subsequent institutional activity. The Arboretum is situated on the
        homelands of the Coast Salish Peoples (specifically the Lummi Nation and
        the Nooksack Tribe), who have lived in the Salish Sea basin, throughout
        the San Juan Islands and the North Cascades watershed, from time
        immemorial.
      </p>
      <h2>1850: Mining</h2>
      <p>
        In the 1850's, coal-mining claims were made on the land known today as
        Fairhaven and Sehome Hill. Two scouts for Henry Roeder's lumber mill,
        Henry Hewitt and William Brown, found coal on the hill. Following this
        discovery, the Bellingham Bay Coal Company was created and mining
        officially began in 1855.
      </p>

      <p>
        Rights to the land were sold to a San Francisco-based company. A city
        developed to support the community shipping the coal from Washington
        state to California. Homes, stores, sailing schooners, and a dock sprung
        up around the mine and were the essence of the newly established town of
        Sehome.
      </p>

      <p>
        At the height of production, the mine employed 125 workers. Because of
        fires, cave-ins, floods, poor mining, and a volatile economy, the number
        of workers diminished dramatically. All of this caused the mine to
        intermittently close until its permanent abandonment in 1878. The town's
        population fell to 100 people in the beginning of the 1880's.
      </p>

      <h2>1891: Donating and Surveying Land</h2>
      <p>
        Beginning with C.X. Larrabee’s donation, parcels of land were
        distributed to the towns of Fairhaven and New Whatcom in 1891. These
        land parcels created an overlap between the city limits of both towns.
        Many city leaders supported the idea of converting Sehome Hill into a
        park. J. J. Donovan, of the Bloedel Donovan Lumber Mills, surveyed the
        land to get an understanding of the Hill's potential.
      </p>

      <h2>1904: Logging Ceased</h2>
      <p>
        Clear cut logging depleted most of Sehome Hill's old growth ecosystem,
        but this practice ceased in 1904, allowing the Hill once more to be
        covered with various species of tree.
      </p>

