      <h2>1915: The Normal School</h2>
      <p>
        After sixteen years of providing education, the Normal School, currently
        the site of Western Washington University, found itself surrounded by
        the growing Sehome Hill Park. In 1915, the school purchased the area
        behind its building (today Old Main). With that acquisition, the Normal
        School established partial-control over Sehome Park.
      </p>

      <h2>1922: Developing the Parks Amenities</h2>
      <p>
        Huntoon Drive, which was explored in 1922 by the group including members
        of the Bellingham Park Board (and E.T. Mathes), eventually was extended
        to the Sehome Hill Summit. This extension created a looped road starting
        right behind the Normal School and returning back on what is currently
        Arboretum Drive
      </p>

      <p>
        The Drive included a hand-dug tunnel and a parking area at the summit
        with an unobstructed view of the Canadian mountains and Bellingham Bay.
        The parking area quickly became known as the destination to take your
        sweetheart. Both the tunnel and the parking lot exist today.
      </p>
